Durban - In the wake of the murder of British citizen and former KZN philharmonic musician Simon Milliken, the city has allocated R5million to replace severely damaged fencing which encloses Burman Bush Nature Reserve in Morningside.

The city’s head of Parks, Recreation and Culture, Thembinkosi Ngcobo, said crime affected all areas including nature reserves.
He said Burman Bush had been affected by crime in the past few years.
Related ArticlesTwo men robbed a day before Burman Bush killingBurman Bush mugger apprehended“About four years ago a member of the public was killed here, a year after that another person was killed on the north-east side of this reserve and a member of our staff was stabbed. Then just last week we had the killing of Simon Milliken,” he said.AdChoicesADVERTISINGinRead invented by Teads
Ngcobo said four additional 24-hour security personnel would be added to the existing staff of two rangers. The reserve will now be closed from 6pm to 6am and all visitors must sign in and out.

 







